GREP(1)                          User Commands                         GREP(1)

NAME
       grep - print lines that match patterns

SYNOPSIS
       grep [OPTION]... PATTERNS [FILE]...

DESCRIPTION
       grep  searches  for  PATTERNS  in  each  FILE.  PATTERNS is one or
       more patterns separated by newline  characters,  and  grep  prints
       each line that matches a pattern.

       A  FILE  of  -  stands  for  standard input.  If no FILE is given,
       the current directory is searched recursively when -r is given,
       otherwise standard input is read.

OPTIONS
   Pattern selection and interpretation:
       -E, --extended-regexp
              interpret PATTERNS as extended regular expressions (ERE)

       -F, --fixed-strings
              interpret PATTERNS as fixed strings, not regexps

       -G, --basic-regexp
              interpret PATTERNS as basic regular expressions (BRE,
              default)

       -e, --regexp=PATTERNS
              use PATTERNS for matching

       -f, --file=FILE
              take PATTERNS from FILE

       -i, --ignore-case
              ignore case distinctions in patterns and data

       -w, --word-regexp
              match only whole words

       -x, --line-regexp
              match only whole lines

   Output control:
       -c, --count
              print only a count of selected lines per FILE

       --color[=WHEN], --colour[=WHEN]
              use markers to highlight the matching strings; WHEN is
              'always', 'never', or 'auto'

       -l, --files-with-matches
              print only names of FILEs with selected lines

       -L, --files-without-match
              print only names of FILEs with no selected lines

       -m, --max-count=NUM
              stop after NUM selected lines

       -o, --only-matching
              show only nonempty parts of lines that match

       -q, --quiet, --silent
              suppress all normal output

       -s, --no-messages
              suppress error messages

   Output line prefix control:
       -b, --byte-offset
              print the byte offset with output lines

       -H, --with-filename
              print file name with output lines

       -h, --no-filename
              suppress the file name prefix on output

       -n, --line-number
              print line number with output lines

       -T, --initial-tab
              make tabs line up (if needed)

       -Z, --null
              print 0 byte after FILE name

       --label=LABEL
              use LABEL as the standard input file name prefix

   Context control:
       -A, --after-context=NUM
              print NUM lines of trailing context

       -B, --before-context=NUM
              print NUM lines of leading context

       -C, --context=NUM
              print NUM lines of output context

       --group-separator=SEP
              print SEP instead of -- between context groups

       -NUM   same as --context=NUM

   File and directory selection:
       -a, --text
              equivalent to --binary-files=text

       -I     equivalent to --binary-files=without-match

       -r, --recursive
              search files under each directory recursively

       -R, --dereference-recursive
              likewise, but follow all symlinks

       --include=GLOB
              search only files that match GLOB

       --exclude=GLOB
              skip files matching GLOB

       --exclude-dir=GLOB
              skip directories matching GLOB

   Miscellaneous:
       -v, --invert-match
              select non-matching lines

       --help display this help and exit

       -V, --version
              display version information and exit

NOTES
       grep includes a built-in BRE/ERE regex engine with support for
       POSIX character classes ([:alnum:], [:alpha:], etc.).

EXIT STATUS
       0      at least one line was selected

       1      no lines were selected

       2      an error occurred

